{"type":"message","id":"3bd4bb9e","parentId":"f4b26fcb","timestamp":"2026-03-03T23:42:01.122Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_3yhBXIoo24ThlSlXVkOdtggX|fc_0ffb4273e81c90930069a771c8e95481959af88e40a2a6b45e","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# GitHubification\n\n### The method by which a repo can execute using GitHub as Infrastructure\n\n<p align=\"center\">\n  <picture>\n    <img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/japer-technology/githubification/main/.githubification/githubification-logo.png\" alt=\"GitHub-ification\" width=\"500\">\n  </picture>\n</p>\n\nGithubification is the act of converting a repository into GitHub-as-infrastructure. Instead of cloning the repo and running the software elsewhere, the repo becomes something that runs on GitHub itself via GitHub Actions. There’s no separate local runtime to install—GitHub is the runtime.\n\n[![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-yellow.svg)](https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT) ![AI](https://img.shields.io/badge/Assisted-Development-2b2bff?logo=openai&logoColor=white) \n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1772581321122}}
